snippet.textDisplay:
my new years' resolution is to aim for 50 new years' resolutions of some form. I won't evaluate failure or success in any of them until 1st Jan 2021. Hoping for success in 35/50 but we'll see. I have 13 decided resolutions on the list so far.


The meta-aim of this is to recover from fear of failure. A degree of failure is built into this plan. For some reason, this is making me excited to get stuck in, not terrified of trying and failing anyway. 10/50 is still a good score, and feels achievable while being a lot more successful resolutions than most people get through. One of the resolutions is the dreaded 'get fit/do more exercise'. If this was my only new years' resolution it would be a bleak grind. As it stands I'm excited to get started, but taking it gradually since I have other resolutions to work on too. People who I care about are noticing general improvement, my wellbeing is up and depression down.

The effect I like the most is that it feels like things are getting better, but I don't feel like I'm getting more time-poor or 'imbalanced' like you do when you focus all your energy and time on one change. that's my strat I recommend it!

snippet.textDisplay:
Themes are actually timeless. By getting the illusion of time and the pressure of supposed deadlines out of the way, you're actually living in the moment. Like you wanna practice music yeah just stop watching YT right now grab your instrument. We're so obsessed with goals that we forgot to enjoy life's moments in this eternal now, thinking that there's gonna be a point later on when we'll get to X and we'll be happy.


Whether you will eventually succeed doesn't matter really, because you have to enjoy right now, today. Live as the person who reads books and have fun with it, no matter if you don't manage to complete 1 every month. Fuck goals and deadlines, live the dream.


Also lifestyle identities help us evolve better. I mean you can't be the "person who listen to 1 music album every day" but you can be "the person obsessed with checking out new music".

snippet.textDisplay:
This is a strange one to me - pretty much every goal-setting lecture I've ever heard is mostly the opposite. According to those, you want Specific goals that are Measurable - "I will read a new book every month for the rest of the year" is something you can set, check and see if you're on-course, and have a timeline for. Whereas "year of reading" is vague enough that you could construe almost any reading done as success.

It's neat to see a counterpoint here.

snippet.textDisplay: Contrary to the video, I successfully lost weight (over 35kg) and kept it off, even though it was not a new year resolution, the way I did it pretty much applies to how I would now set a new year resolution.  The goal must be clear, rather than "get in shape" plan must be measurable, as an example, lost certain amount of weight or drop some % of bodyfat, there must be a deadline too, if it's a year long project, then there must be a monthly or even weekly progression you can track.  And most importantly, detail how you will achieve it within the time frame you give yourself.  This will weed out the pie in the sky ambition that will never happen and with a fully thought out plan, much easier to follow.  I've also done must read 2 non-fiction book every months and succeeded in it too.
snippet.textOriginal: Contrary to the video, I successfully lost weight (over 35kg) and kept it off, even though it was not a new year resolution, the way I did it pretty much applies to how I would now set a new year resolution.  The goal must be clear, rather than "get in shape" plan must be measurable, as an example, lost certain amount of weight or drop some % of bodyfat, there must be a deadline too, if it's a year long project, then there must be a monthly or even weekly progression you can track.  And most importantly, detail how you will achieve it within the time frame you give yourself.  This will weed out the pie in the sky ambition that will never happen and with a fully thought out plan, much easier to follow.  I've also done must read 2 non-fiction book every months and succeeded in it too.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's really nice to have a compartmentalized idea of time, after all the brain loves to put stuff in neat boxes, but you don't have to wait for a specific time point. Some "themes" like say, health which often require some preparation, like better food in the fridge or maybe buying some weights will take a day or something to plan properly to set yourself on the theme. That's okay. It's about waiting for "the right time" that's the problem. What you can wait for is a time in which the theme fits your current life. So insetad of after so and so's birthday in 5 months to excuse your starting point, you could instead think "just went to the grocery store already, I am tired and don't want to go again. Next time I go, pick healthier foods, or maybe skip that one bad thing you often get". Making this plan and having an idea of where to go has already started the theme. You already started. There was no need to pick a perfect time. You have a plan that continues the theme, not starts it. Planning is part of starting. Getting an idea is already starting your theme.

Smaller changes help in staying with the theme and it's hard on you if you set overarching big goals at a set time frame, because big picture is too much in the fog of time. Once you have your theme, start to think about really tiny goals that keep you on that theme. It doesn't matter how small, or even if they fail, the point is to try to make choices keeping with the theme. So even if it's not, buy stuff for a nice salad and is instead getting a diet soda instead of regular, and still buying that box of cookies, you are still keeping with that theme. because you still did an action that fits in that broad spectrum of the theme.

If you can't reach your small action to action goal, make it even smaller. Go as small and steady as you need to to stay consistent with the theme.
If 30 min of working out is too much. Try 15. If that's too much, try 7, if that's to much, pick literally one move and do 10 reps or 5, or even 1. Sure, you may have to get down to only working out 1-2 minutes a day for how many times a week you can manage, but you are staying on target, instead of doing everything big for a month and then burning out. Habit building is very difficult. Go with something that is easy to remember, not something you assume will be easy to remember, but that you're able to notice is actually easy to keep up with.

This is especially true for people with mental illnesses, like depression, anxiety, ADHD etc. You need to go with your level of ability and find where you are at, even if you are unhappy with what you can do, you start there first and move up. Soon, you'll be able to do 20 reps. And then maybe even 5 minutes of random exercises. Then 10, then 15. But it's about sticking to that theme, even in small steps. Big leaps that ultimately go nowhere and don't change your habits are doing you no favors. Go as small and as slow as you need to, it truly is better than nothing.


No matter how hopeless or pathetic you think your level of ability is, it doesn't matter, because it is where you are at. Denying it isn't helping you, especially not if you want to improve. Try to accept the reality for what it is, because once you do, you can change it.

snippet.textDisplay: It's kind of funny that CGP Grey's solution to New Years resolutions are to make them as broad as possible, while Veritasium's solution was to make your resolution as precise as possible. Although the one thing they have in common is that your promise will change throughout the year, Grey thinks you will change by finding a different way of fitting the theme than what you were planning for, while Veritasium thinks that as time goes on, that little promise that you made at the start of the year will slowly grow until something bigger by the end of the year. Maybe the willingness to change is the thing that we should take away from both of these outlooks for a better way of life.
